                "content_format": "markdown",
                "content": "## Get in touch\n\nWe're a small, volunteer-run garden, so the best way to reach us depends on what you need. Here's where to start.\n\n## Visit us\n\n**Marshside Community Garden**\nBehind the old fire station on Marsh Lane\n(Look for the green gate and the painted sunflower sign)\n\nThe garden is open to the public **dawn to dusk, every day**. Plot keys are needed only for the tool shed and water spigots.\n\n## Saturday workdays\n\nThe easiest way to reach a coordinator is in person.\n**Saturdays, 9am\u201312pm, April through October.** Coffee is usually on by 9:15.\n\n## Email\n\nFor plot requests, volunteer questions, event ideas, or anything else:\n\n**hello@marshsidegarden.org**\n\nWe're all volunteers, so please give us a few days to reply \u2014 especially during the busy spring and fall months.\n\n## Mailing list\n\nWe send a short email roughly once a month with upcoming workdays, seasonal tips, and garden news. To join, email us with \"subscribe\" in the subject line.\n\n## Frequently asked questions\n\n**Can I visit even if I don't have a plot?**\nYes! The garden is open to everyone during daylight hours. Wander the paths, sit on the bench, say hi to whoever's around.\n\n**Can I bring my kids? My dog?**\nKids, absolutely \u2014 we have a small bed set aside for them. Dogs, sorry, not inside the garden fence (it's a food-growing space), but they're welcome on the path outside.\n\n**I'd like to donate. How?**\nThank you! We accept donations of tools, seeds, compostable materials, and money. Email us and we'll point you in the right direction.\n\n**Who runs the garden?**\nA rotating group of about a dozen neighbor-volunteers, with two coordinators each year. It's genuinely a community project \u2014 no nonprofit staff, no city office, just folks who live nearby."
